10/12/2009
NEW YORK, United States -- UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon's special adviser on Cyprus, Alexander Downer, said on Wednesday (December 9th) that Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders are finding "growing convergence" on many subjects in their talks to reunify the island. Speaking to journalists at the UN headquarters in New York, Downer expressed cautious optimism about the success of the UN-backed negotiations. He and the UN Secretary-General's Special Representative in Cyprus, Taye-Brook Zerihoun, briefed the UN Security Council earlier in the day on recent developments.
Meanwhile, Cypriot President Demetris Christofias and Turkish Cypriot leader Mehmet Ali Talat met in Nicosia on Wednesday to discuss economic matters as part of their ongoing reunification talks. Discussions are continuing Thursday. (UN News Centre, Xinhua - 09/12/09)
